Bin #1 would require another as-yet-unannounced and very large (>> 10-15 MBO) SPR release, which seems increasingly unlikely given that it 1) would be too late to influence elections 2) would expose the country to increased risk/vulnerability (the SPR will already be at historically low levels once currently planned releases are complete) 3) there is not a lot of time remaining on the clock for this Question anyway. The only credible scenario for this outcome would be as a response to a new “black swan” emergency that would develop in the very near term. Fingers crossed we don’t find out what exactly such a trigger would be, all possibilities would be very bad news for us all.

Expecting the depletion of the SPR (per Biden’s long-announced plans) to end in October with ~360 Mbbl remaining. I now think that my previous forecasts badly overestimated the rapidity with which the current outflow would be replaced. The SPR will want to replenish a good fraction of volumes (eventually) with the “medium sour” crude grades that are preferred by most US refineries. The proportion of “light sweet” crude in the SPR is growing and has significant implications for gas prices and ability for the SPR to buffer against any new shocks (e.g., hurricanes, etc.)
